04960nam a22006375i 9780292737655DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212005txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927376557 a10.7560/7058072doi  a(DE-B1597)586731  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 7aLCO0000002bisacsh04a897/.097200aWords of the True Peoples/Palabras de los Seres Verdaderos: Anthology of Contemporary Mexican Indigenous-Language Writers/Antología de Escritores Actuales en Lenguas Indígenas de México :bVolume One/Tomo Uno: Prose/Prosa /ced. by Carlos Montemayor, Donald Frischmann. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2005  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents / Contenido -- tAcknowledgments / Agradecimientos -- tAbbreviations / Abreviaturas -- tPast and Present Writing in Indigenous Languages -- tPasado y presente de la escritura en lenguas indígenas -- tThe Indigenous Word in Mesoamerica -- tLa Palabra indígena mesoamericana -- t1. María Luisa Góngora Pacheco (Maya) -- t2. Jorge Echeverría Lope (Maya) -- t3. Miguel Ángel May May (Maya) -- t4. Santiago Domínguez Aké (Maya) -- t5. Isaías Hernández Isidro (Tabasco Chontal) -- t6. Enrique Pérez López (Tzotzil) -- t7. Jacinto Arias Pérez (Tzotzil) -- t8. Diego Méndez Guzmán (Tzeltal) -- t9. Domingo Gómez Gutiérrez (Tzeltal) -- t10. María Roselia Jiménez (Tojolabal) -- t11. Javier Castellanos Martínez (Sierra Zapotec) -- t12. Joel Torres Sánchez (Purepecha) -- t13. Gabriel Pacheco (Huichol) -- t14. Librado Silva Galeana (Nahuatl) -- t15. Román Güemes Jiménez (Nahuatl) -- tAppendices / Apéndices -- tEnglish Glossary -- tGlosario español0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAs part of the larger, ongoing movement throughout Latin America to reclaim non-Hispanic cultural heritages and identities, indigenous writers in Mexico are reappropriating the written word in their ancestral tongues and in Spanish. As a result, the long-marginalized, innermost feelings, needs, and worldviews of Mexico's ten to twenty million indigenous peoples are now being widely revealed to the Western societies with which these peoples coexist. To contribute to this process and serve as a bridge of intercultural communication and understanding, this groundbreaking, three-volume anthology gathers works by the leading generation of writers in thirteen Mexican indigenous languages: Nahuatl, Maya, Tzotzil, Tzeltal, Tojolabal, Tabasco Chontal, Purepecha, Sierra Zapoteco, Isthmus Zapoteco, Mazateco, Ñahñu, Totonaco, and Huichol. Volume 1 contains narratives and essays by Mexican indigenous writers. Their texts appear first in their native language, followed by English and Spanish translations. Frischmann and Montemayor have abundantly annotated the English, Spanish, and indigenous-language texts and added glossaries and essays that trace the development of indigenous texts, literacy, and writing. These supporting materials make the anthology especially accessible and interesting for nonspecialist readers seeking a greater understanding of Mexico's indigenous peoples. The other volumes of this work will be Volume 2: Poetry/Poesía and Volume 3: Theater/Teatro.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 7aLITERARY COLLECTIONS / General.2bisacsh1 aFrischmann, Donald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrischmann, Donald, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJackson, George O.1 aMontemayor, Carlos, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMontemayor, Carlos, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/70580740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9